<section id="work-first-section">	
	<h1 class="padding-bottom-10">WebMD Mobile App</h1>	
	<p>Personalized medical & health content curation</p> 
</section>
<section class="greybg padding-60">
	<div class="wrapper">
		<img src="images/webmd/three.png" class="three">
	</div>
</section>
<section class="whitebg padding-60">
	<div class="wrapper">
		<div class="lefthalf">
			<h3 class="padding-bottom-20">Project Scope</h3>
			<p>This project was completed for General Assembly's UXDi program over the course of 2 weeks. I developed this project as part of a 3 member team of UX design students to solve a problem for WebMD, a medical information & news website.</p>
		</div>
		<div class="righthalf">
			<h3 class="padding-bottom-20">My Role</h3>
			<p>Our team collaboratively worked on ideation of the solution, research, synthesis and iteration. I took responsibility of wireframing and prototyping. As an extension to the project, I also worked on the visual design and created a high-fidelity mockup of the app.</p>
		</div>
	</div>
</section>
<section class="whitebg">
	<div class="wrapper middle">
		<h3 class="padding-bottom-20">The Challenge</h3>
		<h2 class="padding-bottom-20">A more personalized experience.</h2>
		<p> WebMD wants to increase its user acquisition and retention. The company has come to an understanding that users have difficulty parsing through its massive collection of content. Our challenge was to create an experience that is more personalized and meaningful to the users or someone they are trying to help.</p>	
	</div>
</section>
<section class="whitebg padding-60">	
	<div class="wrapper middle">	
		<h3 class="padding-bottom-20">Solution</h3>
		<h2 class="padding-bottom-20">Relevant content, all in one place.</h2>
		<p>The new, redesigned WebMD mobile app provides users with a personalized experience by curating and presenting relevant medical tips, news, and other content based on their personal information, family history of medical issues, and daily habits.</p>
	</div>
</section>
<section class="greybg padding-60">
	<div class="wrapper text-align-left">
		<div class="lefthalf">
			<h3 class="padding-bottom-20">Process</h3>
			<h2 class="padding-bottom-20">Research, confirm, design.</h2>
			<p class="padding-bottom-20">From our existing knowledge and experience with WebMD, our assumption was simple--users only come to WebMD when they're sick, and do not proactively browse its content to get medical information when they're not.</p>
			<p>To confirm our assumption and to understand the motivation and behavior of our users, we conducted two rounds of surveys. From the <span class="bold">first survey</span> of 190 participants, we learned that:</p>
			<ul>
				<li>71% of the participants have used WebMD before</li>
				<li>But they mostly only used WebMD to diagnose symptoms when they were sick</li>
				<li>Social media feed was the most common medium users chose in receiving medical news and updates</li>
			</ul>
			<p class="padding-bottom-40">From this result, we confirmed that user acquisition wasn't the issue at hand, but we had 	to create a feature that would have these existing users to come back to WebMD on a regular basis.</p>
		</div>
		<div class="righthalf infograph">
		<h3>*Space for infographics*</h3>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="wrapper quote padding-bottom-40">
		<hr>
		<div class="padding-bottom-20 padding-top-20">"Social media feed was the most common method for the users in keeping updated with a certain medical condition."</div>
		<hr>
	</div>
	<div class="wrapper text-align-left">
		<p class="padding-bottom-20">From these insights, we decided to implement the new feature of a personalized news feed based on users' information. This would create a more meaningful experience for users interested in receiving relevant medical news and information. It would also have a more refined content compared to receiving information from a social media feed.</p>
		<p class="padding-bottom-40">To implement this feature, we wanted to make sure that the users would be willing to share their personal information and brief medical history with a secured and private app. So we conducted a <span class="bold">second round of survey</span>, which confirmed that 79% of users who currently suffer from a medical condition/have a history of medical condition would be willing to provide their information in order to receive a more personalized medical information.</p>
		<h2 class="padding-bottom-20">Restructuring the existing features</h2>
		<p>In addition to the new personalized feed feature, we decided on a complete restructuring of the app, while keeping a lot of its existing features which we found to be valuable. Ambiguous section titles were changed, and scattered glossary pages were combined into one search page.</p>
	</div>
</section>
<section class="whitebg padding-60">
	<div id="finaldesign" class="wrapper text-align-left padding-bottom-60">	
		<h3 class="padding-bottom-20">Final Design</h3>
		<h2 class="padding-bottom-20">Introducing the new, personalized WebMD.</h2>
		<p>You can view the WebMD prototype <a href="#" class="webmdhref">here</a>.</p>
	</div>
	<div class="wrapper text-align-left padding-bottom-60">
		<h2 class="padding-bottom-20">Onboarding Flow</h2>
		<p>In the onboarding flow, we wanted to ensure that users knew why asking the personal information, and how it was going to benefit them. We also emphasized the security and privacy of the information, to eliminate as much hesitancy as possible.</p>
	</div>
	<div class="wrapper padding-bottom-60">
		<div class="screen-float-left margin-right-10px">
